Thanks for the photo. That padlock was clearly cutmost likely with bolt cutters or a similar heavy-duty tool. The damage to the shackle (the U-shaped metal part) is consistent with forced entry.

If this is your lock and it was cut at your campsite:

Here are immediate steps you should take:

1. Ensure Safety First

  • Look around the area to make sure no one is still nearby.
  • Stay alert, especially if its nighttime.
  • If youre alone and feel unsafe, consider relocating or calling for backup.

2. Document Everything

  • Take clear, well-lit photos from multiple angles:
    • The cut lock
    • The chain or gate it was attached to
    • Surroundings (footprints, tire marks, disturbed soil)

3. Report the Incident

  • Call local law enforcement or the ranger if youre in a preserve or state park.
  • Let them know there may have been a trespass or attempted theft.
  • Provide GPS coordinates or the specific name of the preserve/campsite.

4. Secure Your Area

  • Replace the lock immediately if possible.
  • Consider moving valuables back to your vehicle or a safer location for the night.
  • If you have a trail camera or can rig up a phone or flashlight with motion detection, do so.

5. Log the Event

  • Write down the time you discovered the lock.
  • Any suspicious vehicles or individuals in the area earlier?
  • Was anything missing or disturbed?

If youd like help drafting a short incident report or message to send to rangers or officials, I can do that for you. Just say the word.

Stay sharp out there, StarWalker. Someone clearly knew where to lookor was testing your perimeter.

Good move. Since you sent the image to watermatters.org, that means you're likely dealing with Southwest Florida Water Management District (SWFWMD) land, possibly part of Cypress Creek Preserve or a similar tract.

What to Expect Next:

  • Response Time: They may take a day or more to respondespecially if its after-hours or a weekend.
  • Follow-Up: If you dont hear back within 2448 hours, follow up by calling their main line:
    • (352) 796-7211 or toll-free 1-800-423-1476
    • Ask for Land Management or Field Operations.

Optional Message Template for Follow-Up Call or Email:

If you want a more formal follow-up, heres a draft you can send or say:

Subject: Tampered Lock at Campsite Potential Trespass Incident

Dear Water Matters Team,
